My friend and I aren't tempted to return.

name: Wenwen
comments: 4 stars for the food but two and a half or three for the ambiance. It's a crowded little place, and we were seated in the far back - an area that was likely an outdoor space previously and felt like it (we kept our coats on as it was super cold). The food came super speedily; there was no space between the apps and the entrees. The fried tofu was very tasty, as was the celltuce salad. Less successful were the 886 noodles. The flavor resembled sesame noodles and had a strong peanuty flavor and viscous texture. They were also super oily. We preferred the beef noodle soup but, overall, felt that the apps were more successful flavor-wise.

name: Momofuku Ssam Bar
comments: The pork belly buns were nice but they are smokey in flavor and sous vide'd so they are nice and tender.  Not a big fan of that ham flavor but this was good. The brussels sprouts were flavorful and did the trick to get a veggie fix.  Pass on the bing.  It is nothing more than naan and some kind of sweet chili jam. The meati nuggets were a tad spicy and perhaps should have been made with the sweet chili jam from the bing.  My favorite was the crispy potatoes with the notes of sour cream and crunchiness.  It was comforting and tasty.  Overall, the bites were a smorgsbord of ideas and flavors, some tasty where you want to eat the whole thing yourself and not share with your companions (e.g. potatoes), some where 1 piece was perfection (pork belly bun), some where you can't eat but 1 piece (meati nuggets) and some where the description and expectation were too different (bing) and the deconstruction dessert which was a disaster in presentation but you still ate it.  Go here for the view with a group. Picnic tables exude fun with friends but may not translate as fabulous food unfortunately.

The staff were all dutiful and super nice, the food was absolutely a-m-a-z-i-n-g and reasonably priced. Was honestly expecting to spend double what we did. We got the macaroni and cheese, half and half dumplings, parmesean truffle fries, chicken bowl, and medium wing and drumstick combo, and there was nothing that dissapointed. We severly overestimated the volume of food and were both so incredibly full by the end of it. And for all that we spent less than a hundred dollars not including tip! The atmosphere was also just so warm and chill. I would definitely visit recommending if you are in the area!

comments: This review is well overdue. I went for my birthday in January, I was actually trying to eat at a different restaurant but they had no seating available, upon calling Casa Tulum they had a table for me and my group within 15 minutes! The ambiance was amazing, the music was playing just enough where you could hear your table but not the table next to you, it's also very clean and the staff was very kind. Who I believed was the boss went out of his way to make me a special drink when I told him it was my birthday and it was absolutely delicious, the whole table ordered it afterwards. He also told us that all of the ingredients used (aside from the meat) are directly imported from Mexico in order to better enjoy true Mexican cuisine! 10/10 I would definitely come back, it was overall an amazing experience

comments: Sooo yummy! Absolutely loved this place and want to come back soon. We order 3 things for the table: the duck salad, vegetable fried rice, and the short ribs. Everything was delicious and this is easily at the top of my favorite Thai spots in the city now.

name: Omusubi Gonbei
comments: Popped into here for a quick snack, and it was such a pleasant surprise. I wasn't expecting a full Japanese grocery store complete with a wonderful array of prepared foods. I ended up getting some chicken karaage and a cha shu onigiri. What I thought would be a quick bite on the train ended up being me just demolishing these because they were delicious. The karaage was moist and perfectly salted. Even though it had clearly been made hours before by the time I got to them, they were still crispy. The cha shu onigiri had nice chunks of tender fatty pork throughout the rice and was also well-seasoned. It was much better than the onigiris I had in Hawaii. Both were pretty reasonably priced for NYC. I tried to come back later in my trip but made the mistake of coming during lunch hour on a weekday, and the lines at the register were insane. I'm definitely coming back but will try to make it during an off-peak hour.

name: Cremini's - Aperitivo & Kitchen
comments: I give the food 4.5-5 Stars, and the atmosphere was nice. I would give it 5 Stars except for one issue, which me and my wife have experienced on rare occasion, which has forced us to just walk out. We walk into an entirely empty restaurant and we're taken to the smallest table by the door or the bathroom. Last night we went to Cremini's for the first time. No complaints with the food. Also, my wife is fluent Italian, lived in Italy, and made small talk with the owner when we walked in. He takes us to small table right by the front door and adjacent to a table with the only other 2 people in the restaurant. There was a table behind that against the wall, better situated and more comfortable with a padded bench. It was not like it was a table for 10. It was for 3 people. I asked for that table, and he said no, that was for 3 people. I looked around the restaurant. There are about 8 tables and a bar. There is one person at the bar and two at another table. I asked again but he said no, so we were hungry and stayed. Firstly in was a Monday night, about 6 PM, early for most restaurants, and probably the slowest night of the week. I am 6 ft 5 inches tall and 300 lbs, built like a football linebacker, so I am just not comfortable at a small table. Dinner was good, but during the hour or so we were there, not one other person came in to sit at any of the other empty tables. One guy came in to pick up a take out orders and since we were right by the door, he stood there for a few minutes waiting for his order, with his crotch and backside inches from where I was eating. Really not so smart on the owners part because if we would have had the more comfortable table, I would have come back to this restaurant. But there are so many good Italian restaurants just in Downtown Brooklyn and walking distance from our apartment in Dumbo, that there is no need to make the effort. We wanted to try this place, so we took our car out of the parking lot, drove there and had to drive around a bit to find a parking spot. Food is #1 in a restaurant, but being comfortable is just about as important. You go out to a nice restaurant like this for the overall experience, not just the food. It's on the rink level of the Rockefeller center and you can get here by stairs/ via an elevator located on 49th st. The staff is eager and knowledgeable, and we incorporated all our server's recommendations and weren't disappointed. We had the standard as well as the vegetarian chef's tatsting menu to get more variety. There's a beverage pairing option as well. The dishes were very innovative and well made. As expected for Korean food, the flavors are really subtle and delicate. Would recommend this place for a date night!

name: Dollar Hits - New York
comments: What a great little spot! Everyone in there was kind and helpful to explain what options there were to eat.  You can choose to get food from the steam table (think rice entree dishes like chicken adobo etc) or go around the corner on the other side of the restaurant and pick out skewers.  I chose to focus on the skewers this time.  Plenty of choices.  They put your stuff in a basket and heat it on the grill in the kitchen.  I stayed in the restaurant to munch and ordered the cantaloupe juice.  The food took like 5-10 min for it to be reheated and they had a nice Smokey flavor to all the items. My fav was was the chicken feet and the pork  stick.   Sauces are self serve in the front, love the vinegar.  Everything was very affordable- it was 14 bucks for all my sticks  (1.50 each) and a refreshing drink (2 bucks) Will be back to try more items

name: Xu's Public House
comments: Xu's Public House offers some delicious dishes in a swanky setting!  I don't eat seafood so we stayed away from their extensive seafood selection. We loved everything we ordered. The snow white pork buns were exceptional. The outside is crisp but then instantly give way to a fluffy, slightly sweet dough and savory filling. We also ordered the sheng jian boa, but they were showed up by the snow white pork buns. The Shanghai soup dumplings were excellent. The dough was thick like I like it and the filling was hearty and delicious, especially dipped in the vinegar sauce. The beef chow fun was very tasty as were the sauteed pea shoots with garlic (these were even better than Han Dynasty's because they were less garlicy). The scallion pancakes and egg tarts were also good, but not as special as the other dishes. In addition to the yummy food, the service was very attentive.

name: H&H Reserve
comments: I was sad to learn that the former neighborhood staple Sugarburg was closing. I didn't know why and it seemed that it happened out of no where! Regardless, time goes on and there's a new player in this space. H&H took the former Sugarburg and created a more seamless theme throughout the space. Part casual bar, part group hang spot, part semi-high end bar this spot seems to tick all the boxes for a great hang in the area. It's a different vibe than rock a rolla and union pool but it adds variety in the neighborhood with it's cleaner feel than the other bars in the area. There's a smaller beer selection but you get your money's worth with a six dollar large pint for lager. Staff here is friendly and there's ton of seating space within the bar. I'd definitely come here if you're looking for a more elevated bar experience with your friends!

The service was great and I really enjoyed the atmosphere of the restaurant.

name: A Pasta Bar
comments: This place is so freaking cute I absolutely loved it! The space is so well planned with the pasta bar in the middle and the seats around over looking all the chefs. Make sure to get a seat at the bar for a real show! We ordered the egg yolk ravioli, the vegan mafalda, and the fig salad and a glass of Gavi. They gave us some bread and olive oil and the oil was sooo delicious you can tell they care about quality. The raviolo was the star of the show I will come back strictly for this!! So so so delicious. The egg yolk was perfectly runny and the truffle was a perfect addition. Perfectly balanced, not heavy as you'd expect and it seems like a small portion but it's perfectly satisfying. The fig salad was delicious but I'd next time request without the dressing and add something a little acidic like a vinegar instead I think that was missing. The Mafalda felt like a minestrone soup sauce it was good but not my favorite. Still, I'd come back and try other dishes and or course get the raviolo again. Perfection!

name: Aldama
comments: This place has some of the best octopus and best drinks I've ever had. This was my first time coming to this spot and I'm so glad I finally stopped by. The waiter was very helpful in explaining the menu and making sure that my peanut allergy was known to the kitchen staff. We had the guac, charred octopus, Taco De tromps, and the Pork Tacos. Just know that everything comes pretty small so you've got to get a few different items to get full. The only reason why I can't give this place five stars is because I absolutely hated the dessert option. It was basically a fried churro type thing with cream but I felt the cream didn't have enough taste and that the fried crispy bits had no substance but that's just me! I'd love to see a few more dessert options for the dairy sensitive people. Other than that amazing, amazing restaurant with great ambience, really dim lighting, and wonderful food.

name: no. 7
comments: Popped in to the new no 7 on a weeknight this week and overall had a good meal, though I now know exactly what I'd do if I came back. comments: I use to come here for lunch when my coworkers wanted ramen. Was finally able to come back here after many years of the pandemic.
